[2
Date: Thu, 26 Mar 1998 15:59:24 +0700
From: PETER ECHEVERRIA <pechev@mozart.inet.co.th>

A lot of people have looked, but the _Yersinia_ that can be isolated are
not pathogenic. The age is a little old but this is reminescent of Pigbe
l(enteritis necroticans) in Surin [sic and elsewhere in Asia.
How about trying anaerobic cultures for _Clostridium perfringens_? The
problem is telling the beta toxin+ from those that are non toxigenic. This
epidemic is described in Lancet by Johnson, S et al 1987:ii:496-500. As I
remember, after J. Sakurai had shown that these isolates produced beta
toxin, Drs Eampokalap and Kimakorn, I think at Rama and Chula
[universities? prepared the gross description and tissue blocks, and
these blocks were examined by Cooke and Lawrence in Australia. Could we
report cp [ _Clostridium perfringens_ in Cambodian children. I think we
still have some reprints of Stu's paper if anyone is interested.
--
Peter Echeverria M. D.
Afrims, Bangkok, Thailand
